# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: black-pepper
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] In humans, arachidonate 12-lipoxygenase (12-LO, 12-LOX, ALO12, or platelet type 12-lipoxygenase) is encoded by the ALOX12 gene and expressed primarily in platelets and skin.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Arachidonate 12-lipoxygenase, 12R type, also termed 12RLOX and encoded by the ALOX12B gene, is expressed primarily in skin and cornea; it metabolizes arachidonic acid to 12(*R*)-HpETE.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Cytochrome P450 enzymes convert arachidonic acid to a variety of hydroperoxy, epoxy, and dihydroxy derivatives including racemic mixtures of 12(*S*)-HpETE and 12(*R*)-HpETE or 12(*S*)-HETE and 12(*R*)-HETE; the *R* stereoisomer predominates in these mixtures.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Mice also express an epidermal type 15-lipoxygenase (e-12LO) which has 50.8% amino acid sequence identity to human 15-LOX-2 and 49.3% sequence identity to mouse arachidonate 8-lipoxygenase.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Mouse e-12LO metabolizes arachidonic acid predominantly to 12(*S*)-HETE and to a lesser extent 15(*S*)-HETE.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Sub-human primates, although not extensively examined, appear to have 12-lipoxygenase expression patterns that resemble those of sub-primate mammals or humans depending on the closeness of there genetic relatedness to these species.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] In human (and mouse) skin epidermis, 12(*R*)-HpETE is metabolized by Epidermis-type lipoxygenase, i.e. eLOX3 (encoded by the ALOXE3 gene), to two products: a) a specific hepoxilin, 8*R*-hydroxy-11*R*,12*R*-epoxy-5*Z*,9*E*,14*Z*-eicosatetraenoic acid (i.e.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] These decompositions may occur during tissue isolation procedures.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] In other tissues and animal species, numerous hepoxilins form but the hepoxilin synthase activity responsible for their formation is variable.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Thus, the production of hepoxilins from 12(S)-HpETE may result from the intrinsic activity of platelet or leukocyte type 12-LOX's, require eLOX3, or even result from 12(*S*)-HpETE spontaneous (and perhaps artefactual) decomposition during isolation.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The majority of reports on hepoxilin formation have not defined the pathways evolved.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Human and other mammalian cytochrome P450 enzymes convert 12(*S*)-HpETE to 12-oxo-ETE.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 12-HETE (stereoisomer not determined), 12(*S*)-HETE, 12-oxo-ETE, hepoxilin B3, and trioxilin B3 are found in the *sn*-2 position of phospholipids isolated from normal human epidermis and human psoriatic scales.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] This indicates that the metabolites are acylated into the *sn*-2 position after being formed and/or directly produced by the metabolism of the arachidonic acid at the *sn*-2 position of these phospholipids.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] These acylation reactions may sequester and thereby inactivate or store the metabolites for release during cell stimulation.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The G protein-coupled receptor, GPR31, cloned from PC3 human prostate cancer cell line is a high affinity (Kd=4.8 nM) receptor for 12(*S*)-HETE; GPR31 does not bind 12(*R*)-HETE and has relatively little affinity for 5(*S*)-HETE or 15(*S*)-HETE.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] In PC-3 prostate cancer cells, GPR31 receptor mediates the action of 12(*S*)-HETE in activating the mitogen-activated protein kinase kinase/extracellular signal-regulated kinases-1/2 pathway and NFκB pathway that lead to cell growth and other functions.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Studies have not yet determined the role, if any, in GPR31 receptor in the action of 12(*S*)-HETE in other cell types.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] A G protein-coupled receptor for the 5(*S*),12(*R*)-dihydroxy metabolite of arachidonic acid, leukotriene B4, vis., leukotriene B4 receptor 2 (BLT2), but not its leukotriene B4 receptor 1, mediates responses to 12(*S*)-HETE, 12(*R*)-HETE, and 12-oxo-ETE in many cell types.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The BLT2 receptor, in contrast to the GPR31 receptor, appears to be expressed at a high level in a wide range of tissues including neutrophils, eosinophils, monocytes, spleen, liver, and ovary.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] However, 12-hydroxyheptadecatrienoic acid (i.e.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 12-(*S*)-hydroxy-5*Z*,8*E*,10*E*-heptadecatrienoic acid or 12-HHT), a product made when prostaglandin H2 is metabolized to thromboxane A2 by thromboxane synthase or spontaneously rearranges non-enzymatically is the most potent BLT2 receptor agonist detected to date.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Ultimately, both receptors and all three ligands may prove to be responsible for some tissue responses in vivo.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 12(*S*)-HETE and 12(*R*)-HETE bind to and act as competitive antagonists of the thromboxane receptor which mediates the actions of thromboxane A2 and prostaglandin H2.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] This antagonistic activity was responsible for the ability of 12(*S*)-HETE and 12(*R*)-HETE to relax mouse mesenteric arteries pre-constricted with a thromboxane A2 mimetic, U46619.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 12(*S*)-HETE binds with high affinity to a 50 kilodalton (kDa) subunit of a 650 kDa cytosolic and nuclear protein complex.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Since it mediates 12(*S*)-HETE-induced itching in the mouse model, BLT2 rather than GPR31 may mediate human itch in these reactions.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 12-HETE (stereoisomer not defined) is the dominant arachidonic acid metabolite in cultured PC3 human prostate cancer cells and its levels in human prostate cancer tissue exceed by >9-fold its levels in normal human prostate tissue.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] These results suggest that the 12(*S*)-HETE made by prostate cancer tissues serves to promote the growth and spread of this cancer.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Since it mediates the action of 12(*S*)-HETE in stimulating cultured PC3 cells to activate the mitogen-activated protein kinase kinase/extracellular signal-regulated kinases-1/2 pathway and NFκB pathways, the GPR31 receptor may contribute to the pro-malignant activity of 12(*S*)-HETE.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Thus, the role of 12(*S*)-HETE in human prostate cancer, if any, may involve its activation of one or both of the GPR31 and BLT2 receptors.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] These studies implicate the interaction of 12-HETE with BLT2 receptors in intestinal epithelium cancer cells, and BLT2 receptors in breast, ovary, pancreas, and bladder cancer cells.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] While the studies on these tissues have not been as frequent or diverse as those on prostate cancer cell lines, they are suggested to indicate that 12-HETE contributes to the growth or spread of the corresponding cancer in humans.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 12(S)-HETE, 12(*S*)-HpETE, and with far less potency 12(*R*)-HETE reduced insulin secretion and caused apoptosis in cultured human pancreatic insulin-secreting beta cell lines and prepared pancreatic islets.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 12-lipoxygenase-knockout mice (i.e., mice genetically manipulated to remove the Alox12, i.e.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 12-lipoxygenase gene, see Lipoxygenase § Mouse lipoxygenases) are resistant to **a)** streptozotocin-induced, **b)** high fat diet-induced, and **c)** autoimmune-induced diabetes.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Further studies in animal models suggest that the 12*S*-HETE made by pancreatic beta cells (or possibly alpha cells or other cell types indigenous to or invading the pancreatic islands) orchestrate a local immune response that results in the injury and, when extreme, death of beta cells.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] These results suggest that the 12-lipoxygenase-12S-HETE pathway is one factor contributing to immunity-based type I diabetes as well as low insulin output type II diabetes.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The vasodilating effect on mouse mesenteric arteries appears due to 12*S*-HETE's ability to act as a thromboxane receptor antagonist and thereby block the vasoconstricting actions of thromboxane A2.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] These results indicate that the cited metabolites have dilating or constricting effects that depend on the arterial vascular site and or species of animal examined; their role in human blood pressure regulation is unclear.
[src:black-pepper/12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Excessive 12-HETE production is implicated in psoriasis.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Some recent studies measuring HODE levels in tissue have lumped the four 9-HODEs with the four 13-HODEs to report only on total HODEs (tHODEs). tHODEs have been proposed to be markers for certain human diseases.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] The enzyme acts in a highly stereospecific manner, forming 13(*S*)-hydroperoxy-9*Z*,11*E*-octadecadienoic acid (13(*S*)-HpODE) but comparatively little or no 13(*R*)-hydroperoxy-9*Z*,11*E*-octadecadienoic acid (13(*R*)-HpODE) -.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] In cells, 13(*S*)-HpODE is rapidly reduced by peroxidases to 13(*S*)-HODE.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] ALOX15 is fully capable of metabolizing the linoleic acid that is bound to phospholipid or cholesterol to form 13(S)-HpODE-bound phospholipids and cholesterol that are rapidly converted to their corresponding 13(S)-HODE-bound products.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Concurrently with their production of 13(*S*)-HODE, these enzymes also produce smaller amounts of 9(*R*)-HODE.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Cytochrome P450 microsomal enzymes metabolize linoleic acid to a mixture of 13-HODEs and 9-HODEs; these reactions produce racemic mixtures in which the *R* stereoisomer predominates, for instance by a *R*/*S* ratio of 80%/20% for both 13-HODE and 9-HODE in human liver microsomes.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] 4-hydroxy-2*E*-nonenal or HNE) is also a peroxidation product of 13-HpODE.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Since oxidative stress commonly produces both free radicals and singlet oxygen, most or all of these products may form together in tissues undergoing oxidative stress.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Free radical and singlet oxygen oxidations of linoleic acid produce a similar set of 13-HODE metabolites (see 9-Hydroxyoctadecadienoic acid).
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Studies attribute these oxidations to be major contributors to 13-HODE production in tissues undergoing oxidative stress including in humans sites of inflammation, steatohepatitis, cardiovascular disease-related atheroma plaques, neurodegenerative disease, etc.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] 13(*S*)-HODE is also metabolized by peroxisome-dependent β-oxidations to chain-shortened 16-carbon, 14-carbon, and 12-carbon products which are released from the cell; this chain-shortening pathway may serve to inactive and dispose of 13(*S*)-HODE.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] 13(*S*)-HODE is oxidized to 13-oxo-9*Z*,11*E*-octadecadienoic acid (13-oxo-HODE or 13-oxoODE) by a NAD+-dependent 13-HODE dehydrogenase, the protein for which has been partially purified from rat colon.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Colonic mucosal explants from Sprague-Dawley rats and human colon cancer HT29 cells add glutathione to 13-oxo-ODE in a Michael reaction to form 13-oxo-9-glutatione-11(*E*)-octadecenoic acid; this conjugation reaction appears to be enzymatic and mediated by a glutathione transferase.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Since this conjugate may be rapidly exported from the cell and has not yet been characterized for biological activity, it is not clear if this transferase reaction serves any function beyond removing 13-oxo-ODE from the cell to limit its activity.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] 13-HODE, 13-oxoODE, and 13-EE-HODE (along with their 9-HODE counterparts) directly activate peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma (PPARγ).
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] This activation appears responsible for the ability of 13-HODE (and 9-HODE) to induce the transcription of PPARγ-inducible genes in human monocytes as well as to stimulate the maturation of these cells to macrophages.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] 13(*S*)-HODE, 13(*R*)-HODE and 13-oxoODE, along with their 9-HODE counterparts, also act on cells through TRPV1.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] TRPV1 is the transient receptor potential cation channel subfamily V member 1 receptor (also termed capsaicin receptor or vanilloid receptor 1).
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] The OXLAM-TRPV1 interaction is credited with mediating pain sensation in rodents (see below).
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] 13(*S*)-HpODE, and 13(*S*)-HODE directly activate human (but not mouse) GPR132 (G protein coupled receptor 132, also termed G2A) in Chinese hamster ovary cells made to express these receptors; they are, however, far weaker GPR132 activators than 9(*S*)-HpODE or 9(*S*)-HODE.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] GPR132 was initially described as a pH sensing receptor; the role(s) of 13(*S*)-HpODE and 13(*S*)-HODE as well as 9(*S*)-HpODE, 9(*S*)HODE, and a series or GPR132-activating arachidonic acid hydroxy metabolites (i.e.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] HETEs) in activating G2A under the physiological and pathological conditions in which G2A is implicated (see GPR132 for a lists of these conditions) have not yet been determined.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] This determination, as it might apply to humans, is made difficult by the inability of these HODEs to activate rodent GPR132 and therefore to be analyzed in rodent models.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] It is suggested that the accumulation of phospholipid-bound 13(*S*)-HpODE and/or 13(*S*)-HODE is a critical step in rendering mitochondria more permeable thereby triggering their degradation and thence maturation to erythrocytes.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] However, functional inactivation of the phospholipid-attacking lipoxygenase gene in mice does not cause major defects in erythropoiesis.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] It is suggested that mitochondrial degradation proceeds through at least two redundant pathways besides that triggered by lipoxygenase-dependent formation of 13(*S*)-HpODE- and 13(*S*)-HODE-bound phospholipids viz., mitochondrial digestion by autophagy and mitochondrial exocytosis.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] In all events, formation of 13(*S*)-HODE bound to phospholipid in mitochondrial membranes is one pathway by which they become more permeable and thereby subject to degradation and, as consequence of their release of deleterious elements, to cause cell injury.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] These effects may contribute to the pro-inflammatory and tissue-injuring actions ascribed to 13-HODEs (and 9-HODEs).
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] In atherosclerosis, an underlying cause of Coronary artery disease and strokes, atheromatous plaques accumulate in the vascular tunica intima thereby narrowing blood vessel size and decreasing blood flow.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] In an animal model and in humans 13-HODE (primarily esterified to cholesterol, phospholipids, and possibly other lipids) is a dominant component of these plaques.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] The 13(*S*)-HODE/PPARγ axis also causes macrophages to self-destruct by activating apoptosis-inducing pathways;, this effect may also contribute to increases in plaque size.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] These studies suggest that 13-HODE-producing metabolic pathways, PPARγ, CD36, and aP2 may be therapeutic targets for treating atherosclerosis-related diseases.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Indeed, Statins, which are known to suppress cholesterol synthesis by inhibiting an enzyme in the cholesterol synthesis pathway, 3-hydroxy-3-methyl-glutaryl-CoA reductase HMG-CoA reductase, are widely used to prevent atherosclerosis and atherosclerosis-related diseases.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Statins also inhibit PPARγ in human macrophages, vascular endothelial cells, and smooth muscle cells; this action may contribute to their anti-atherogenic effect.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] In guinea pigs, 13(*S*)-HODE, when injected intravenously, causes a narrowing of lung airways and, when inhaled as an aerosol, mimics the asthmatic hypersensitivity to agents that cause bronchoconstriction by increasing airway narrowing responses to methacholine and histamine.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Familial adenomatous polyposis is a syndrome that includes the propensity to develop colorectal cancer (and other cancers) due to the inheritance of defective mutations in either the APC (adenomatous polyposis coli) or MUTYH gene.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] These mutations lead to several abnormalities in the regulation of the growth of colon epithelial cells that ultimately lead to the development of intestinal polyps which have a high risk of turning cancerous.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Similarly selective reductions in 15-lipoxygenase 1 and 13-HODE occur in non-hereditary colon cancer.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] 13(*S*)-HODE inhibits the proliferation and causes the death (apoptosis) of cultured human colon cancer cells.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] Animal model studies also find that the 15-lipoxygenase 1 / 13-HODE axis inhibits the development of drug-induced colon cancer as well as the growth of human colon cancer cell explants.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] The results of these studies suggest that 13(*S*)-HODE may act to promote the growth of breast cancer in humans.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] These 15-LOX 1 effects appear due to the enzyme's production of 13(*S*)-HODE.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] The 15-LOX 1/13(**S**)-HODE axis also promotes the growth of prostate cancer in various animal models.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] In one animal model the pro-growth effects of 15-LOX 1 were altered by dietary targeting: increases in dietary linoleic acid, an omega-6 fatty acid, promoted while increases in dietary stearidonic acid, an omega-3 fatty acid reduced the growth of human prostate cancer explants.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] The level of total HODEs, which includes various 13-HODE and 9-HODE isomers, are elevated in the plasma and erythrocytes of patients with Alzheimer's disease and in the plasma but not erythrocytes of patients with vascular dementia compared to normal volunteers.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] See 9-hydroxyoctadecadienoic acid section on 9-HODEs as markers of disease involving oxidative stress for further details.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] These studies suggest that high levels of the HODEs may be useful to indicate the presence and progression of the cited diseases.
[src:black-pepper/13-hydroxyoctadecadienoic-acid] HODE markers may find usefulness as markers of specific disease, type of disease, and/or progression of disease when combined with other disease markers.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] A subset of cytochrome P450 (CYP450) microsome-bound ω-hydroxylases, the cytochrome P450 omega hydroxylases, metabolize arachidonic acid to 20-HETE by an omega oxidation reaction.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] CYP450 enzymes belong to a superfamily which in humans is composed of at least 57 members and in mice at least 120 members.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] However, CYP2U1 may also contribute to the production of these two HETEs and CYP4F8 can metabolize arachidonic acid to 19-HETE while forming little or no 20-HETE.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The production of 19-HETE with 20-HETE may be significant since 19(*R*)-HETE, although not its stereoisomer, 19(*S*)-HETE, inhibits the action of 20-HETE on vascular endothelial cells.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Based on studies analyzing the production of other HETEs by CYP enzymes, the production of 19-HETE by these enzymes may include both its *R* and *S* stereoisomers.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] In humans, the CYP4 ω-hydroxylases include CYP4A11, CYP4F2, and CYP4F3 with the predominant 20-HETE-synthesizing enzymes being CYP4F2, which is the major 20-HETE producing enzyme in the human kidney, followed by CYP4A11.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] CYP4F3 is expressed as two distinct enzymes, CYP4F3A and CYP4F3B, due to alternative splicing of a single pre-mRNA precursor molecule; CYP4F3A is mostly expressed in leukocytes, CYP4F3B mostly in the liver.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Human CYP4Z1, which is expressed in a limited range of tissues such as human breast and ovary, may also metabolize arachidonic acid to 20-HETE while human CYP4A22, once considered as contributing to 20-HETE production, is now regarded as being metabolically inactive.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Finally, CYP2U1, the only member of the human CYP2U subfamily, is highly expressed in brain and thymus and to lesser extents in numerous other tissues such as kidney, lung and heart.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] CYP2U1 protein is also highly expressed, compared to several other cytochrome P450 enzymes, in malignant breast tissue; the MCF-7 human breast cancer cell line express messenger RNA for this cytochrome.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] In mice, the only 20-HETE- and 19-HETE-producing enzymes of the Cyp4a subfamily are two extensively homologous ones, Cyp4a12a and Cyp4a12b; Cyp4a12a is expressed in the male kidney in an androgen hormone-dependent manner.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The tissue distribution of these enzymes differs from those of humans making extrapolations from rodent studies to humans somewhat complicated.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Mouse CYP2J9, rat CYP2J3, and sheep CYP2J metabolize arachidonic acid primarily to 19-HETE but also to smaller amounts of 20-HETE, and, in the case of the sheep enzyme, 18-HETE; human CYP2J2, however, is an epoxygenase, metabolizing arachidonic acid to epoxide products.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Many agents stimulate cells and tissues to produce 20-HETE in vitro and in vivo.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Androgens are particularly potent stimulators of this production.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Other stimulators include the powerful vasoconstriction-inducing agents, angiotensin II, endothelins, and alpha adrenergic compounds (e.g. norepinephrine).
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Nitric oxide, carbon monoxide, and superoxide inhibit 20-HETE production; these non-pharmacological agents do so by binding to the Heme binding site of the 20-HETE producing cytochrome p450 enzymes.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Drugs that are substrates for the UDP-glucuronosyltransferase (UGT) enzymes which metabolize 20-HETE such as non-steroidal anti-inflammatory agents, opioids, gemfibrozil, Lasix, propanol, and various COX-2 inhibitors may act as perhaps unwanted side effects to increase the levels of 20-HETE.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] There are a variety of pharmacological agents which inhibit the synthesis of 20-HETE including various fatty acid analogs that compete reversibly with arachidonic acid for the substrate binding site in the CYP enzymes and benzene-based drugs.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The cytochrome ω-oxidases including those belonging to the CYP4A and CYP4F sub-families and CYPU21 hydroxylate not only arachidonic acid but also various shorter chain (e.g. lauric acid) and/or longer chain (e.g. docosahexaenoic acid) fatty acids.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] They can also ω-hydroxylate and thereby reduce the activity of various fatty acid metabolites (e.g.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] LTB4, 5-HETE, 5-oxo-eicosatetraenoic acid, 12-HETE, and several prostaglandins) that regulate inflammation, vascular responses, and other reactions.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] This metabolism-induced inactivation may underlie the proposed roles of the cytochromes in dampening inflammatory responses and the reported associations of certain CYP4F2 and CYP4F3 single nucleotide variants with human Krohn's disease and Coeliac disease, respectively.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Glucuronidation of 20-HETE by UDP-glucuronosyltransferases (UGTs) is thought to be a primary pathway of 20-HETE elimination and thereby inactivation in humans.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] There are several other pathways that metabolize 20-HETE.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] However, the 20-hydroxy prostaglandin metabolites are able to contract rat aorta rings and thereby could contribute to the hypertensive actions of 20-HETE.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Coronary artery endothelial cells isolated from pigs incorporate 20-HETE primarily into the sn-2 position of phospholipids through a coenzyme A-dependent process.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] It is likely, although not yet shown, that these mouse and pig 20-HETE metabolizing pathways also occur in humans.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 20-HETE-synthesizing enzymes are widely distributed to liver, kidney, brain, lung, intestine and blood vessels.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] In most vascular systems, 20-HETE synthesizing activity is limited to vascular smooth muscle of small blood vessels with little or no such activity in the vessel's endothelial cells or in large blood vessels.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] However, both the smooth muscle and endothelial cells obtained from mouse brain microvasculature, produce 20-HETE in culture.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 20-HETE is produced by human neutrophils and platelets and by the ascending tubule cells in the medulla as well the pre-glomerular arterioles and certain other localized areas of the rabbit kidney.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Other agents such as Androgens and alpha adrenergic compounds such as norepinephrine. likewise stimulate 20-HETE production and have vasoconstrictive actions which are enhanced by 20-HETE.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] These circular or positive feedback interactions may serve to perpetuate vasoconstrictor responses.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Again in rodent models, 20-HETE acts to block Calcium-activated potassium channels to promote the entry of ionic calcium into vascular smooth muscle cells through the L-type calcium channel; the attendant rise in intracellular calcium triggers these muscles to contract.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Studies in rats also indicate that in vascular endothelial cells 20-HETE inhibits the association of the nitric oxide-producing enzyme, endothelial nitric oxide synthase (eNOS) with heat shock protein 90; this inhibits the ability of eNOS to become activated.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 20-HETE can also constrict rodent (and human) artery preparations by directly activating the receptor for thromboxane A2.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Acting in the latter capacity, 20-HETE, it is proposed, functions as a mediator regulating blood flow to the brain.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Sprague Dawley rats that underwent balloon injury of the common carotid artery exhibited elevated levels of CYP4A enzyme immunostaining in the smooth muscle of the injured arteries as well as elevated levels of 20-HETE in the injured arteries.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Inhibition of 20-HETE production by two different agents greatly reduced the vascular intima hyperplasia and vascular remodeling that occurred after balloon injury.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The studies suggest that the increase in expression of CYP4A and production of 20-HETE contribute to vascular intima growth, remolding, and thereby healing of injured rat carotid arteries.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The endothelial, platelet, and pro-clotting actions of 20-HETE may contribute to its ability to disrupt blood flood to tissues.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] As indicated above, 20-HETE may raise blood pressure by constricting arterial blood vessels but also may lower blood pressure by promoting the loss of sodium and fluids in the kidneys.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The effects of 20-HETE therefore are complex, as indicated in studies of the following animal models.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Spontaneously hypertensive rats exhibit elevated levels of CYP4A2 and 20-HETE; blockade of 20-HETE production lowers blood pressure in this model.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The effect is particularly well seen in female rats: aging post-menopausal but not pre-menopausal female spontaneously hypertensive rats exhibit highly significant falls in blood pressure when treated with non-selective or selective inhibitors of CYP-induced 20-HETE production.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Dahl salt-sensitive rats develop hypertension that develops more quickly and exacerbated by high intake of salt (sodium chloride) and ameliorated by low salt intake.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] In this model, rats exhibit an up-regulated CYP4A/20-HETE pathway within their cerebral vasculature and vascular endothelial cell overproduction of reactive oxygen species that in turn stimulates the CYp4A/20-HETE pathway.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Non-selective and non-selective inhibitors of CYP4A and 20-HETE production reduce hypertension in this model.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The hypertension in this model is more severe in male rats and appears to be mediated at least in part by vasopressin, the renin-angiotensin system, and androgens.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Lewis rats (see Laboratory rat models) that had one kidney removed and then fed a high salt diet are hypertensive.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Androgen treatment causes hypertension in normal male and female rats; this hypertensive response is greatly reduced by diverse inhibitors of Cyp4a and 20-HETE production.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Cyp4a12-transgenic mice overexpressing Cyp4a12 develop androgen-independent hypertension that is associated with increased levels of 20-HETE; this hypertension is fully reversible by treatment with a Cyp4a selective inhibitor of 20-HETE production.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Mice depleted of Cyp4a14 by gene knockout (Cyp4a14(-/-) mice develop male-specific, androgen-dependent hypertension.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] This seemingly paradoxical result is due to the overexpression of Cyp4a12a; the knockout of Cyp4a14 (Cyp4a14 does not produce 20-HETE) leads to the overexpression of the 20-HETE-producing cytochrome, Cyp4a149(-/-), and consequent overproduction of 20-HETE.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The Cyp4a12-transgenic model (above) is referred to in support of this presumption.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Mice depleted of Cyp4a10 maintain normal blood pressure on a low salt diet but become hypertensive on normal or high salt diets; this paradoxical result appears due to a decrease in kidney levels of Cyp2C44 caused by the loss of Cyp4a10.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Cyp2C44 metabolizes arachidonic acid a family of vasodilation-inducing and anti-hypertensive products, the Epoxyeicosatrienoic acids (EETs).
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 20-HETE activates the mouse and human transient receptor potential cation channel subfamily V member 1 (TRPV1, also known as the capsaicin receptor and the vanilloid receptor 1), and through this receptor, cultured dorsal root ganglion cells taken from mice.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Human CYP4A11 has 72.69% amino acid identity with murine cyp4a14 and 73.02% identity with murine cyp4a10 suggesting that it plays a role in humans similar to that of cyp4a14 and/or cyp4a10 in mice.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The association of hypertension with defective CYP4A11 in humans as indicated below seems to parallel the hypertension associated with Cyp4a14 gene knockout in mice (see above section on genetic models).
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The effect of the −296C>T single base pair substitution on baseline CYP411 transcriptional activity was not significant, suggesting that this polymorphism may not be the causal variant but instead may be in linkage disequilibrium with the causal variant.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Regardless, this SNP may serve as a genetic marker for large vessel disease stroke risk in this population.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] This variant of the CYP4F2 enzyme has reduced capacity to metabolize arachidonic acid to 20-HETE but increased urinary excretion of 20-HETE.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The maintenance of the lower blood pressure that followed diet-induced weight loss was more difficult for carriers of the Val433Met variant and may be related to increased arterial stiffness and increased 20-HETE synthesis.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The incidence of cerebral and myocardial infarction in these studies appears to be independent of hypertension.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] (The platelets of individuals heterozygous or homozygous for the Val433Met variant exhibit increased platelet aggregation responses to epinephrine.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The Single-nucleotide polymorphism rs1558139 guanine to cytosine variant in an intron of CYP4F2 is associated with essential hypertension in men only in a study of 249 hypertensive versus 238 age-matched controls in Japan.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The impact of this variant on CYP4F2 expression is not known.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Researchers have identified at least 3 more single-nucleotide polymorphisms of *CYP4F2* (2024C>G P85A; 80 C>T A27V rs771576634; 139C>T R47C rs115517770) which may affect conversion of arachidonic acid to HETE-20.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] A mutation (c.947A>T) in CYP2U1 has been associated with a small number of patients with Hereditary spastic paraplegia in that it segregates with the disease at the homozygous state in two afflicted families.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] A second homozygous enzyme-disabling mutation has been identified in CYP2U1, c.1A>C/p.Met1?, that is associated with <1% of hereditary spastic paraplegia sufferers.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] While the role of 20-HETE in these mutations has not been established, the reduction in 20-HETE production and thereby 20-HETE's activation of the TRPV1 receptor in nerve tissues, it is hypothesized, may contribute to the disease.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Two human breast cancer cell lines, T47D and BT-474, made to overexpress CYP4Z1 by transfection overexpress messenger RNA for and overproduce vascular endothelial growth factor A while under expressing message and protein for tissue inhibitor of metalloproteinase-2.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] T47D cells that overexpress CYP4Z1 also overproduce 20-HETE and when transplanted into athymic Balb/c mice show a greater increase in tumor weight and vascularity compared to control T47D cells; these increases are prevented by an inhibitor of 20-HETE production.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Isoliquiritigenin, a proposed drug for treating cancer, cause cultured MDA-MB-231 and MCF-7 human breast cancer cells to die by triggering apoptosis.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Among its many other effects, the drug caused these cells to decrease their levels of 20-HETE in vitro; the addition of 20-HETE to these cultures rescued the cells from apoptosis.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Isoliquiritigenin also inhibits the in vivo lung metastasis of MDA-MB-231 cell transplants while concurrently decreasing the tumor's levels of 20-HETE.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The growth of MDA-MB-231 cells implanted into athymic nude female mice as well as the cells' production of a large variety of agents stimulating vascularization including vascular endothelial growth factor were inhibited by treating the mice with an inhibitor of 20-HETE production.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Messenger RNAs not only for CYP4Z2 but also for CYP4A11, CYP4A22, CYP4F2, and CYP4F3 are more highly expressed in samples of human breast cancer tumors compared to normal breast tissue.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The Three prime untranslated regions (3'UTRs) of the CYP4Z1 gene and its Pseudogene, CYP4Z2P, share several miRNA-binding sites, including those for miR-211, miR-125a-3p, miR-197, miR-1226, and miR-204'.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Taken together, these pre-clinical studies suggest that 20-HETE made by one or more of the cited cytochrome P450 enzymes may contribute to the progression of breast cancer by promoting its survival, growth, and vascular endothelial growth factor-induced neovascularization.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 20-HETE stimulated the proliferation of cultured human brain Glioma cell line U251 and, when forced to overexpress CYP4Z1 by gene transfection, overproduced 20-HETE and exhibited a dramatically increased rate of growth that was blocked by inhibiting the cells from producing 20-HETE.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] A similar set of findings was found with human non-small cell lung cancer cells.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] A selective inhibitor of 20-HETE synthesis and a 20-HETE antagonist reduced the growth of two human kidney cancer 786-O and 769-P cell lines in culture; the 20-HETE antagonist also inhibited the growth of 786-O cells transplanted into athymic nude mice.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Ovarian cancers also overexpress CYP4Z1 mRNA protein; this overexpression is associated with a poorer disease outcome.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] While these studies suggest that CYP4A11, CYP4A22, CYP4F2, and/or CYP4F3 produce 20-HETE which in turn promotes the growth of the cited cancers in model systems and therefore may do so in the human cancers, this suggestion clearly needs much further study.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] It is also possible that any such inhibitor has off-target effects that are responsible for its actions.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 20-HETE inhibits the aggregation of human platelets by competing with arachidonic acid for the enzymes that produce prostaglandin H2 and thromboxane A2.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] These products are formed in response to platelet stimulation and then act through the thromboxane receptor to mediate and/or promote the ensuing platelet aggregation response to most stimuli.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] The platelets metabolize 20-HETE to the 20-hydroxy analogs of prostaglandin H2 and thromboxane A2, products that are essentially inactive in platelets, while consequently form less of the arachidonic acid-derived prostaglandin and thromboxane products.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] In addition, 20-HETE itself blocks prostaglandin and thromboxane metabolites from interacting with the thromboxane receptor.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Both effects, i.e. replacement of prostaglandin and thromboxane production with platelet-inactive products and thromboxane A2 receptor blockade, are responsible for 20-HETE's platelet aggregation-inhibiting action.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] However, the platelet anti-aggregating activity of 20-HETE requires micromolar levels and therefore may be more of a pharmacological than physiological activity.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] 20-HETE constricts human artery preparations by directly activating the receptor for thromboxane A2.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] Acting in the latter capacity, 20-HETE, it is proposed, functions as a mediator regulating blood flow to the human brain.
[src:black-pepper/20-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic-acid] One study found that 30 patients with the metabolic syndrome exhibited significantly elevated levels of plasma and urinary 20-HETE compared to matched controls; women with the syndrome had particularly higher urinary 20-HETE levels.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] Skatole is one of the volatile compounds in human breath associated with halitosis.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] It is used as a fragrance and fixative in many perfumes and as an aroma compound.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] It is also used in low concentrations in some ice cream as a flavor enhancer.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] Its name derives from the Greek root *skato-*, meaning feces.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] Skatole was discovered in 1877 by the German physician Ludwig Brieger (1849–1919).
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] Skatole is derived from the amino acid tryptophan in the digestive tract of mammals.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] Tryptophan is converted to indoleacetic acid, which decarboxylates to give the methylindole.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] Once it is created in the digestive tract of mammals, it is metabolized by cytochrome P450 enzymes in the liver.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] Skatole can be prepared in the laboratory via the Fischer indole synthesis, a method for the formation of indole derivatives from phenylhydrazines and carbonyl compounds.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] Phenylhydrazine and propanal can be used.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] A simplified reaction scheme is shown below.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] It gives a violet color upon treatment with potassium ferrocyanide.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] Skatole is one of many compounds that are attractive to males of various species of orchid bees, which apparently gather the chemical to synthesize pheromones; it is commonly used as bait for these bees for study.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] It is also known for being an attractant for the Tasmanian grass grub beetle (*Aphodius tasmaniae*).
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] Skatole has been shown to be an attractant to gravid mosquitoes in both field and laboratory conditions.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] Because this compound is present in feces, it is found in combined sewage overflows (CSO), as streams and lakes containing CSO water have untreated human and industrial waste.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] CSO sites are thus of particular interest when studying mosquito-borne diseases such as West Nile virus.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] The release of skatole by certain parasitic wasps in the family Bethylidae is used to determine which subfamily the species belongs to.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] Species of the Epyrinae subfamily release skatole, while those in the Bethylinae subfamily release a different chemical, spiroacetal.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] Skatole occurs naturally in the feces of all species of mammals and birds, and in the bovine rumen.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] Skatole has been shown to cause pulmonary edema in goats, sheep, rats, and some strains of mice.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] It appears to selectively target club cells, which are the major site of cytochrome P450 enzymes in the lungs.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] These enzymes convert skatole to a reactive intermediate, 3-methyleneindolenine, which damages cells by forming protein adducts (see fog fever).
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] With the testicular steroid androstenone, skatole is regarded as a principal determinant of boar taint.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] High amounts of skatole stored in the fat tissue of pigs corresponds with boar taint.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] To address this, vaccinations with an immunogenic amount of *Lawsonia intracellularis* antigen are being studied.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] This antigen reduces the uptake of skatole into the fat of pigs, thus reducing the effect of boar taint.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] Another method used to address skatole concentration in fat tissue is supplementing the pig's diet with 3% chestnut wood extract.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylindole] This method showed that intestinal skatole concentration decreased by more than 50%.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylphenol] Together with many other compounds, *m*-cresol is traditionally extracted from coal tar, the volatile materials obtained in the production of coke from (bituminous) coal.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylphenol] This residue contains a few percent by weight of phenol and isomeric cresols.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylphenol] In the cymene–cresol process, toluene is alkylated with propylene to give isomers of cymene, which can be oxidatively dealkylated analogous to the cumene process.
[src:black-pepper/3-methylphenol] Another method, involves carbonylation of a mixture of methallyl chloride and acetylene in the presence of nickel carbonyl.
[src:black-pepper/4-hydroxynonenal] Early identification and characterization of 4-hydroxynonenal was reported by Esterbauer, et al., who also obtained the same compound synthetically.
[src:black-pepper/4-hydroxynonenal] The topic has since been often reviewed, and one source describes the compound as "the most studied LPO (lipid peroxidation) product with pleiotropic capabilities".
[src:black-pepper/4-hydroxynonenal] 4-Hydroxynonenal is generated in the oxidation of lipids containing polyunsaturated omega-6 fatty acids, such as arachidonic and linoleic acids, and of their 15-lipoxygenase metabolites, namely 15-hydroperoxyeicosatetraenoic and 13-hydroperoxyoctadecadienoic acids.
[src:black-pepper/4-hydroxynonenal] Although they are the most studied ones, in the same process other oxygenated α,β-unsaturated aldehydes (OαβUAs) are generated also, which can also come from omega-3 fatty acids, such as 4-oxo-trans-2-nonenal, 4-hydroxy-trans-2-hexenal, 4-hydroperoxy-trans-2-nonenal and 4,5-epoxy-*trans*-2-decenal.
[src:black-pepper/4-hydroxynonenal] 4-HNE can attach to proteins via a Michael addition reaction, which can target cysteine, histidine or lysine, or through the formation of a Schiff base, which can target arginine or lysine.
[src:black-pepper/4-hydroxynonenal] The lysine adduct ((4-HNE)-lysine or 4-hydroxynonenallysine) has been referred to as an "oxidation-specific epitope" and a lipid oxidation "degradation product".
[src:black-pepper/4-hydroxynonenal] It is generated by the oxidative modification of low-density lipoprotein through the direct addition of carbonyl groups from 4-HNE onto lysine.
[src:black-pepper/4-hydroxynonenal] These compounds can be produced in cells and tissues of living organisms or in foods during processing or storage, and from these latter can be absorbed through the diet.
[src:black-pepper/4-hydroxynonenal] Since 1991, OαβUAs are receiving a great deal of attention because they are being considered as possible causal agents of numerous diseases, such as chronic inflammation, neurodegenerative diseases, adult respiratory distress syndrome, atherogenesis, diabetes and different types of cancer.
[src:black-pepper/4-hydroxynonenal] HNE has been linked to the pathology of several diseases such as Alzheimer's disease, cataract, atherosclerosis, diabetes and cancer.
[src:black-pepper/4-hydroxynonenal] The increasing trend to enrich foods with polyunsaturated acyl groups entails the potential risk of enriching the food with some OαβUAs at the same time, as has already been detected in some studies carried out in 2007.
[src:black-pepper/4-hydroxynonenal] PUFA-fortified foods available on the market have been increasing since epidemiological and clinical researches have revealed possible effects of PUFA on brain development and curative and/or preventive effects on cardiovascular disease.
[src:black-pepper/4-hydroxynonenal] However, PUFA are very labile and easily oxidizable, thus the maximum beneficial effects of PUFA supplements may not be obtained if they contain significant amounts of toxic OαβUAs, which as commented on above, are being considered as possible causal agents of numerous diseases.
[src:black-pepper/4-hydroxynonenal] Special attention must also be paid to cooking oils used repeatedly in catering and households because in those processes very high amounts of OαβUAs are generated and they can be easily absorbed through the diet.
[src:black-pepper/4-hydroxynonenal] 4-HNE has two reactive groups: the conjugated aldehyde and the C=C double-bond, and the hydroxy group at carbon 4.
[src:black-pepper/4-hydroxynonenal] The α,β-unsaturated ketone serves as a Michael acceptor, adding thiols to give thioether adducts.
[src:black-pepper/4-hydroxynonenal] A small group of enzymes are specifically suited to the detoxification and removal of 4-HNE from cells.
[src:black-pepper/4-hydroxynonenal] Within this group are the glutathione S-transferases (GSTs) such as hGSTA4-4 and hGST5.8, aldose reductase, and aldehyde dehydrogenase.
[src:black-pepper/4-hydroxynonenal] These enzymes have low Km values for HNE catalysis and together are very efficient at controlling the intracellular concentration, up to a critical threshold amount, at which these enzymes are overwhelmed and cell death is inevitable.
[src:black-pepper/4-hydroxynonenal] Glutathione S-transferases hGSTA4-4 and hGST5.8 catalyze the conjugation of glutathione peptides to 4-hydroxynonenal through a conjugate addition to the alpha-beta unsaturated carbonyl, forming a more water-soluble molecule, GS-HNE.
[src:black-pepper/4-hydroxynonenal] This result strongly suggests that hGSTA4-4 and hGST5.8 are specifically adapted by human cells for the purpose of detoxifying 4-HNE to abrogate the downstream effects which such a buildup would cause.
[src:black-pepper/4-hydroxynonenal] Increased activity of the mitochondrial enzyme aldehyde dehydrogenase 2 (ALDH2) has been shown to have a protective effect against cardiac ischemia in animal models, and the postulated mechanism given by the investigators was 4-hydroxynonenal metabolism.
[src:black-pepper/4-hydroxynonenal] GS-HNE is a potent inhibitor of the activity of glutathione S-transferase, and therefore must be shuttled out of the cell to allow conjugation to occur at a physiological rate.
[src:black-pepper/4-hydroxynonenal] Ral-interacting GTPase activating protein (RLIP76, also known as Ral-binding protein 1), is a membrane-bound protein which has high activity towards the transport of GS-HNE from the cytoplasm to the extracellular space.
[src:black-pepper/4-hydroxynonenal] This protein accounts for approximately 70% of such transport in human cell lines, while the remainder appears to be accounted for by Multidrug Resistance Protein 1 (MRP1).
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Black pepper is native to Southeast or South Asia.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Ground, dried, and cooked peppercorns have been used since antiquity, both for flavour and as a traditional medicine.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Black pepper is one of the most commonly traded spices in the world.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Its spiciness is due to the chemical compound piperine, which is a different kind of spiciness from that of capsaicin characteristic of chilli peppers.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] It is ubiquitous in the Western world as a seasoning and is often paired with salt and available on dining tables in shakers or mills.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The word *pepper* derives from Old English *pipor, Latin piper, and* Greek: πέπερι.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The Greek likely derives from Dravidian *pippali*, meaning "long pepper".
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] In the 16th century, people began using *pepper* to also mean the New World chilli pepper (genus *Capsicum*), which is not closely related.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The pepper plant is a perennial woody vine growing up to 4 m (13 ft) in height on supporting trees, poles, or trellises.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] It is a spreading vine, rooting readily where trailing stems touch the ground.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The leaves are alternate, entire, 5 to 10 cm (2 to 4 in) long and 3 to 6 cm (1 to 2+1⁄2 in) across.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The flowers are small, produced on pendulous spikes 4 to 8 cm (1+1⁄2 to 3 in) long at the leaf nodes, the spikes lengthening up to 7 to 15 cm (2+3⁄4 to 6 in) as the fruit matures.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] A single stem bears 20 to 30 fruiting spikes.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The fruit of the black pepper is a drupe and when dried is known as a peppercorn.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Within the genus *Piper*, black pepper is most closely related to other Asian species such as *P. caninum*.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Processed peppercorns come in a variety of colours, any one of which may be used in food preparation, especially common peppercorn sauce.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Black pepper is produced from the still-green, unripe drupe of the pepper plant.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The drupes are cooked briefly in hot water, both to clean them and to prepare them for drying.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The heat ruptures cell walls in the pepper, accelerating enzymes that cause browning during drying.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The pepper drupes can also be dried in the sun or by machine for several days, during which the pepper skin around the seed shrinks and darkens into a thin, wrinkled black layer containing melanoidin.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Once dry, the spice is called black peppercorn.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] After the peppercorns are dried, pepper powder for culinary uses is obtained by crushing the berries, which may also yield an essential oil by extraction.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] White pepper consists solely of the seed of the ripe fruit of the pepper plant, with the thin darker-coloured skin (flesh) of the fruit removed.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] This is usually accomplished by a process known as retting, where fully ripe red pepper berries are soaked in water for about a week so the flesh of the peppercorn softens and decomposes; rubbing then removes what remains of the fruit, and the naked seed is dried.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Sometimes the outer layer is removed from the seed through other mechanical, chemical, or biological methods.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Ground white pepper is commonly used in Chinese, Thai, and Portuguese cuisines.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] It finds occasional use in other cuisines in salads, light-coloured sauces, and mashed potatoes as a substitute for black pepper, because black pepper would visibly stand out.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] However, white pepper lacks certain compounds present in the outer layer of the drupe, resulting in a different overall flavour.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Green pepper, like black pepper, is made from unripe drupes.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Dried green peppercorns are treated in a way that retains the green colour, such as with sulphur dioxide, canning, or freeze-drying.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Pickled peppercorns, also green, are unripe drupes preserved in brine or vinegar.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Fresh, unpreserved green pepper drupes are used in some cuisines like Thai cuisine and Tamil cuisine.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Their flavour has been described as "spicy and fresh", with a "bright aroma." They decay quickly if not dried or preserved, making them unsuitable for international shipping.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Red peppercorns usually consist of ripe peppercorn drupes preserved in brine and vinegar.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Ripe red peppercorns can also be dried using the same colour-preserving techniques used to produce green pepper.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Pink peppercorns are the fruits of the Peruvian pepper tree, *Schinus molle*, or its relative, the Brazilian pepper tree, *Schinus terebinthifolius*, plants from a different family (Anacardiaceae).
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] As they are members of the cashew family, they may cause allergic reactions, including anaphylaxis, for persons with a tree nut allergy.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The bark of *Drimys winteri* ("canelo" or "winter's bark") is used as a substitute for pepper in cold and temperate regions of Chile and Argentina, where it is easily found and readily available.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] In New Zealand, the seeds of kawakawa (*Piper excelsum*), a relative of black pepper, are sometimes used as pepper; the leaves of *Pseudowintera colorata* ("mountain horopito") are another replacement for pepper.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Several plants in the United States are also used as pepper substitutes, such as field pepperwort, least pepperwort, shepherd's purse, horseradish, and field pennycress.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Black pepper is native either to Southeast Asia or South Asia, perhaps including the Malabar Coast of India where the Malabar pepper is extensively cultivated.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Wild pepper grows in the Western Ghats region of India.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Into the 19th century, the forests contained expansive wild pepper vines, as recorded by Scottish botanist Francis Buchanan.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Deforestation resulted in wild pepper growing in more limited forest patches from Goa to Kerala, with the wild source gradually decreasing as the quality and yield of the cultivated variety improved.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Pepper grows in soil that is neither too dry nor susceptible to flooding, moist, well-drained, and rich in organic matter.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The vines grow best under 900 m (3,000 ft) above sea level.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The plants are propagated by cuttings about 40 to 50 cm (16 to 20 in) long, usually cultivars selected both for yield and quality of fruit.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] These are tied up to neighbouring trees or climbing frames at distances of about 2 m (6+1⁄2 ft) apart; trees with rough bark are favoured over those with smooth bark, as the pepper plants climb rough bark more readily.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Competing plants are cleared away, leaving only sufficient trees to provide shade and permit free ventilation.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The roots are covered in leaf mulch and manure, and the shoots are trimmed twice a year.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] On dry soils, the young plants require watering every other day during the dry season for the first three years.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The plants bear fruit from the fourth or fifth year, and then typically for seven years.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Harvesting begins as soon as one or two fruits at the base of the spikes begin to turn red, and before the fruit is fully mature, and still hard; if allowed to ripen completely, the fruits lose pungency, and ultimately fall off and are lost.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The spikes are collected and spread out to dry in the sun, then the peppercorns are stripped off the spikes.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Black pepper has been known to Indian cooking since at least 2000 BCE.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Innes Miller notes that while pepper was grown in southern Thailand and in Malaysia started in early 10th to the 11th century when the South Indian Kings began to extend their empire.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The crop was brought to East Malaysia in 1840 by Chinese settlers; its most important source was India, particularly the Malabar Coast, in what is now the state of Kerala.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The lost ancient port city of Muziris of the Chera Dynasty, famous for exporting black pepper and various other spices, is mentioned in a number of classical historical sources for its trade with the Roman Empire, Egypt, Mesopotamia, Levant, and Yemen.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The ancient history of black pepper is often interlinked with (and confused with) that of long pepper, the dried fruit of closely related *Piper longum*.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The Romans knew of both and often referred to either as just *piper*.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] In fact, the popularity of long pepper did not entirely decline until the discovery of the New World and of chilli peppers.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Chilli peppers—some of which, when dried, are similar in shape and taste to long pepper—were easier to grow in a variety of locations more convenient to Europe.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Before the 16th century, pepper was being grown in Java, Sunda, Sumatra, Madagascar, Malaysia, and everywhere in Southeast Asia.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] These areas traded mainly with China, or used the pepper locally.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Ports in the Malabar area also served as a stop-off point for much of the trade in other spices from farther east in the Indian Ocean.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The Maluku Islands, historically known as the "Spice Islands", are a region in Indonesia known for producing nutmeg, mace, cloves, and pepper, and were a major source of these spices in the world.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The presence of these spices in the Maluku Islands sparked European interest to buy them directly in the 16th century.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Black pepper was a well-known and widespread, if expensive, seasoning in the Roman Empire.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Apicius' *De re coquinaria*, a third-century cookbook probably based at least partly on one from the first century CE, includes pepper in a majority of its recipes.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] In the 18th century, Edward Gibbon wrote that pepper was "a favorite ingredient of the most expensive Roman cookery".
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] In the third century CE, black pepper made its first definite appearance in Chinese texts, as *hujiao* or "foreign pepper".
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] It does not appear to have been widely known at the time, failing to appear in a fourth-century work describing a wide variety of spices from beyond China's southern border, including long pepper.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] By the 12th century, however, black pepper had become a popular ingredient in the cuisine of the wealthy and powerful, sometimes taking the place of China's native Sichuan pepper (the tongue-numbing dried fruit of an unrelated plant).
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Marco Polo testifies to pepper's popularity in 13th-century China, when he relates what he is told of its consumption in the city of Kinsay (Hangzhou): "...
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Pepper's exorbitant price during the Middle Ages – and the monopoly on the trade held by Venice – helped motivate the Portuguese to seek a sea route to India.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] In 1498, Vasco da Gama became the first person to reach India by sailing around Africa; asked by Arabs in Calicut (who spoke Spanish and Italian) why they had come, his representative replied, "we seek Christians and spices".
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Though this first trip to India by way of the southern tip of Africa was only a modest success, the Portuguese quickly returned in greater numbers and eventually gained much greater control of trade on the Arabian Sea, including through the 1494 Treaty of Tordesillas.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] However, the Portuguese monopolised the spice trade for 150 years.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Portuguese even became the lingua franca of the then known world.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] However, in the 17th century, the Portuguese lost most of their valuable Indian Ocean trade to the Dutch and the English, who, taking advantage of the Spanish rule over Portugal during the Iberian Union (1580–1640), occupied by force almost all Portuguese interests in the area.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The pepper ports of Malabar began to trade increasingly with the Dutch in the period 1661–1663.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] As pepper supplies into Europe increased, the price of pepper declined (though the total value of the import trade generally did not).
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Pepper, which in the early Middle Ages had been an item exclusively for the rich, started to become more of an everyday seasoning among those of more average means.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Today, pepper accounts for one-fifth of the world's spice trade.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] In 2023, world production of black peppercorns was 855,105 tonnes, led by Vietnam with 30% of the total, and Brazil, Indonesia, and India as secondary producers.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Peppercorns are among the most widely traded spice in the world, accounting for 20% of all spice imports.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Pepper gets its spicy heat mostly from piperine derived from both the outer fruit and the seed.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Black pepper contains between 4.6 and 9.7% piperine by mass, and white pepper slightly more than that.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Refined piperine, by weight, is about one percent as hot as the capsaicin found in chilli peppers.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The outer fruit layer, left on black pepper, also contains aroma-contributing terpenes, including germacrene (11%), limonene (10%), pinene (10%), alpha-phellandrene (9%), and beta-caryophyllene (7%), which give citrusy, woody, and floral notes.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] These scents are mostly missing in white pepper, as the fermentation and other processing removes the fruit layer (which also contains some of the spicy piperine).
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Other flavours also commonly develop in this process, some of which are described as off-flavours when in excess: Primarily 3-methylindole (pig manure-like), 4-methylphenol (horse manure), 3-methylphenol (phenolic), and butyric acid (cheese).
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Pepper loses flavour and aroma through evaporation, so airtight storage helps preserve its spiciness longer.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Pepper can also lose flavour when exposed to light, which can transform piperine into nearly tasteless isochavicine.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Once ground, pepper's aromatics can evaporate quickly; most culinary sources recommend grinding whole peppercorns immediately before use for this reason.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Handheld pepper mills or grinders, which mechanically grind or crush whole peppercorns, are used for this as an alternative to pepper shakers that dispense ground pepper.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Spice mills, such as pepper mills, were found in European kitchens as early as the 14th century, but the mortar and pestle used earlier for crushing pepper have remained a popular method for centuries, as well.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Enhancing the flavour profile of peppercorns (including piperine and essential oils), prior to processing, has been attempted through the postharvest application of ultraviolet-C light (UV-C).
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] One tablespoon (6 grams) of ground black pepper contains moderate amounts of vitamin K (13% of the daily value or DV), iron (10% DV), and manganese (18% DV), with trace amounts of other essential nutrients, protein, and dietary fibre.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Like many Eastern spices, pepper was historically both a seasoning and a traditional medicine.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Pepper appears in the Buddhist *Samaññaphala Sutta*, chapter five, as one of the few medicines a monk is allowed to carry.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Long pepper, being stronger, was often the preferred medication, but both were used.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Black pepper (or perhaps long pepper) was believed to cure several illnesses, such as constipation, insomnia, oral abscesses, sunburn, and toothaches, among others.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Pepper contains phytochemicals, including amides, piperidines, and pyrrolidines.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Some sources say that piperine, a substance present in black pepper, irritates the nostrils, causing the sneezing.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Few, if any, controlled studies have been carried out to answer the question.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Black peppercorns were found stuffed in the nostrils of Ramesses II, placed there as part of the mummification rituals shortly after his death in 1213 BCE.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Little else is known about the use of pepper in ancient Egypt and how it reached the Nile from the Malabar Coast of India.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Pepper (both long and black) was known in Greece at least as early as the fourth century BCE, though it was probably an uncommon and expensive item that only the very rich could afford.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Peppercorns were a much-prized trade good, often referred to as "black gold" and used as a form of commodity money.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The legacy of this trade remains in some Western legal systems that recognise the term "peppercorn rent" as a token payment for something that is, essentially, a gift.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] By the time of the early Roman Empire, especially after Rome's conquest of Egypt in 30 BCE, open-ocean crossing of the Arabian Sea direct to Chera dynasty southern India's Malabar Coast was near routine.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Details of this trading across the Indian Ocean have been passed down in the *Periplus of the Erythraean Sea*.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] According to the Greek geographer Strabo, the early empire sent a fleet of around 120 ships on an annual trip to India and back.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The fleet timed its travel across the Arabian Sea to take advantage of the predictable monsoon winds.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Returning from India, the ships travelled up the Red Sea, from where the cargo was carried overland or via the Nile-Red Sea canal to the Nile River, barged to Alexandria, and shipped from there to Italy and Rome.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The rough geographical outlines of this same trade route would dominate the pepper trade into Europe for a millennium and a half to come.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] As ships could sail directly to Malabar's coast, Malabar black pepper trade route became shorter than long pepper, reflected in its prices.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] He does not state whether the 50 million was the actual amount of money which found its way to India or the total retail cost of the items in Rome; elsewhere, he cites a figure of 100 million sesterces.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Pepper was so valuable that it was often used as collateral or even currency.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The taste for pepper (or the appreciation of its monetary value) was passed on to those who would see Rome fall.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Alaric, king of the Visigoths, included 3,000 pounds of pepper as part of the ransom he demanded from Rome when he besieged the city in the fifth century.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] After the fall of Rome, others took over the middle legs of the spice trade, first the Persians and then the Arabs; Innes Miller cites the account of Cosmas Indicopleustes, who travelled east to India, as proof that "pepper was still being exported from India in the sixth century".
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] By the end of the Early Middle Ages, the central portions of the spice trade were firmly under Islamic control.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Once into the Mediterranean, the trade was largely monopolised by Italian powers, especially Venice and Genoa.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The rise of these city-states was funded in large part by the spice trade.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] It is commonly believed that during the Middle Ages, pepper was often used to conceal the taste of partially rotten meat.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] No evidence supports this claim, and historians view it as highly unlikely; in the Middle Ages, pepper was a luxury item, affordable only to the wealthy, who certainly had unspoiled meat available, as well.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] In addition, people of the time certainly knew that eating spoiled food would make them sick.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Similarly, the belief that pepper was widely used as a preservative is questionable; it is true that piperine, the compound that gives pepper its spiciness, has some antimicrobial properties, but at the concentrations present when pepper is used as a spice, the effect is small.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Salt is a much more effective preservative, and salt-cured meats were common fare, especially in winter.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] However, pepper and other spices played a role in improving the taste of long-preserved meats.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Archaeological evidence of pepper consumption in late medieval Northern Europe comes from excavations on the Danish-Norwegian flagship, Gribshunden, which sank in the summer of 1495.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] In 2021, archaeologists recovered more than 2,000 peppercorns from the wreck, along with a variety of other spices and exotic foodstuffs including clove, ginger, saffron, and almond.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The ship was carrying King Hans to a political summit at the time of its loss.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The spices were likely intended for feasts at the summit, which would have included the Danish, Norwegian, and Swedish Councils of State.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] It is possible that black pepper was known in China in the second century BCE, if poetic reports regarding an explorer named Tang Meng (唐蒙) are correct.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] Sent by Emperor Wu to what is now south-west China, Tang Meng is said to have come across something called *jujiang* or "sauce-betel".
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] He was told it came from the markets of Shu, an area in what is now the Sichuan province.
[src:black-pepper/black-pepper] The traditional view among historians is that "sauce-betel" is a sauce made from betel leaves, but arguments have been made that it actually refers to pepper, either long or black.
